coredata.dc:description:
In this study, novel core-shell catalyst with a new ternary heterostructure was synthesized (Fe0@POCN/CQDs) for the degradation of tetracycline (TC). The TEM results showed that the Fe0 particles were wrapped in POCN material and many nano CQDs were uniformly dispersed in the material. The new ternary nanocomposite exhibits excellent photocatalytic activity for the removal of TC, which was approximately 4.76 times higher than that of GCN. The enhancement of photocatalytic activity was attributed to the effective heterojunction as well as the multiply synergistic effects of POCN combined with Fe0 and CQDs, which was beneficial for retardation of recombination rate of photogenerated electron–hole pairs and generation of more free radicals for the oxidation of TC. Besides, the reactive oxygen species (ROS) of h+, •O2 − and •OH played pivotal roles in the degradation of TC by Fe0@POCN/CQDs during the photocatalytic reaction. At the same times, sulfate radical (SO4
•-
) and hydroxyl radical (•OH) highlighted the dominant role in the degradation process compared with other free radicals under persulfate hybrid mixture system (PS system), which was further confirmed by radical scavenger experiments and electron spin resonance (ESR) analysis. The response surface methodology (RSM) study indicated that the optimal removal parameters of tetracycline could reach 97.57% within 30 min under PS system. In addition, the possible degradation pathway intermediates of TC were studied by HPLC-MS and the reaction catalytic activity mechanism of Fe0@POCN/CQDs/persulfate system was discussed.

ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
In this study, novel core-shell catalyst with a new ternary heterostructure was synthesized (Fe0@POCN/CQDs) for the degradation of tetracycline (TC). The TEM results showed that the Fe0 particles were wrapped in POCN material and many nano CQDs were uniformly dispersed in the material. The new ternary nanocomposite exhibits excellent photocatalytic activity for the removal of TC, which was approximately 4.76 times higher than that of GCN. The enhancement of photocatalytic activity was attributed to the effective heterojunction as well as the multiply synergistic effects of POCN combined with Fe0 and CQDs, which was beneficial for retardation of recombination rate of photogenerated electron–hole pairs and generation of more free radicals for the oxidation of TC. Besides, the reactive oxygen species (ROS) of h+, •O2 − and •OH played pivotal roles in the degradation of TC by Fe0@POCN/CQDs during the photocatalytic reaction. At the same times, sulfate radical (SO4
•-
) and hydroxyl radical (•OH) highlighted the dominant role in the degradation process compared with other free radicals under persulfate hybrid mixture system (PS system), which was further confirmed by radical scavenger experiments and electron spin resonance (ESR) analysis. The response surface methodology (RSM) study indicated that the optimal removal parameters of tetracycline could reach 97.57% within 30 min under PS system. In addition, the possible degradation pathway intermediates of TC were studied by HPLC-MS and the reaction catalytic activity mechanism of Fe0@POCN/CQDs/persulfate system was discussed.

ce:section.ce:para:
In order to solve the drawbacks of GCN, researchers have adopted extensive methods to modify the materials for the properties of the materials optimization. Aiming at decreasing the band gap, Zhang et al. (2019a) adopted element doping modification to solve this problem. The band gap of the prepared photocatalyst is significantly reduced compared with GCN. Which meant that it can absorb visible light with larger wavelength. Aiming at reducing the recombination of photo-generated electron-hole pairs, Wang et al. (2017) successfully prepared core-shell quantum heterojunction photocatalyst TiO2@g-C3N4 by semiconductor recombination modification. The modified material not only can provide more active sites for photocatalytic reaction, but also the effective electron transfer between titanium dioxide and graphite carbon nitride, which can significantly enhance the photo-current intensity by significantly inhibiting the recombination rate of photo-generated electron-hole pairs (
                     Tonda et al., 2014
                     ).

Recent studies have shown that the advanced oxidation processes (AOPs) are promising advanced oxidation technologies, as oxidizing agent was added to the reaction system will continuously generated free reactive species at the solid/aqueous interface，which can significantly improve the oxidation ability of the photocatalyst (
                     Zhu et al., 2018). SO4

                        •-
                      oxide species can be generated by persulfate (PS) or peroxymonosulfate (PMS) (
                     Wang and Wang, 2018
                     ). Persulfate (S2O8
                     2−) can be activated by thermal, ultraviolet rays, alkaline, metal ions and activated carbon (Liu et al., 2014; Izadifard et al., 2017
                     ). Meanwhile, the existing form of oxide species in the solution will also change with the different pH (
                     Kang et al., 2019). Carbon quantum dots (CQDs) is a new type of zero-dimensional carbon nanomaterial, which has the characteristics of easy preparation, low toxicity, good biocompatibility and good light stability (
                     Li et al., 2017; Xu et al., 2019
                     ). In addition, the response wavelength of carbon dots can be extended from near infrared to visible light, which is a material with excellent optical performance and has broad prospects in the field of photocatalytic materials. At the same time, CQDs has high quantum efficiency and can generate a large number of photo-generated electron-hole pairs during photocatalysis (
                     Li et al., 2019
                     ).

Fig. S2(a) presented the XRD pattern of GCN, POCN, Fe0@POCN and Fe0@POCN/CQDs. It can be observed that GCN mainly has two diffraction peaks, located at 2θ = 13.1° and 27.6°, corresponding to (100) and (002) crystal planes respectively, which was consistent with the results obtained from previous studies(
Peng et al., 2021
). The characteristic diffraction peak of POCN was almost similar with that of GCN, but the intensities of the above peaks were obviously lower than those of the latter, which indicated that the modified material did not change the structure of the raw material, but the crystallinity was reduced. From the XRD pattern of Fe0@POCN, two new diffraction peaks can be observed compared with POCN, located at 2θ = 44.79° and 65.08°, respectively. Corresponding to the (110) and (200) crystal planes of nano zero-valent iron (JCPDS 060696) (
Wu et al., 2019
). At the same time, the intensities of the peaks located at 13.1° and 27.6° are lower than POCN, indicating that the structure of the material were kept unchanged while the material was successfully compounded. Interestingly, the XRD pattern of Fe0@POCN/CQDs was basically was almost similar with that of Fe0@POCN, and no new characteristic peaks appeared in the synthesized materials with the introduction of CQDs. This phenomenon could be due to the diffraction peaks of CQDs at 26° were too weak to be observed, which was relatively small quantity of CQDs in the Fe0@POCN/CQDs (
Zhang et al., 2018a
).

It is well known that solution pH is the most important reaction conditions for the photocatalytic performance of catalysts, which mainly due to the stability of Fe0@POCN/CQDs is related to the pH of the solution (Kong et al., 2019). To investigate the Fe0@POCN/CQDs pH adaptability, effects of the initial pH (3, 5, 7, 9, 11 and 13) of the solution on the photocatalytic performance were carried out. Fig. 2(c) depicted the TC removal efficiency varied with different initial pH. It was observed that, when the solution pH increased from 3 to 7, the removal efficiency of TC increased from 62.1% to 86.7% by Fe0@POCN/CQDs within 60 min. When the solution was under acid pH, the scavenging effects of H+ ion on ·OH limited the removal rate of TC, that is why the obtained the higher TC degradation efficiency under neutral conditions (
                           Yan et al., 2019a
                           ). But as the pH value was further increased to 13, the removal of TC significantly decreased to 59.8%. When the solution was under alkaline pH, the high OH− concentration tended to generate the active oxide species quencher CO3
                           2−, which reacted with the active species generated in the photocatalytic process to reduce the photocatalytic performance (
                           Yan et al., 2019b
                           ).

Effects of different of Fe0@POCN/CQDs dosage (20, 25, 30, 35, 40 and 45 mg) on degradation of TC were evaluated. As shown in Fig. 2(d), The TC degradation efficiency increased with the increasing Fe0@POCN/CQDs dosages. When 20 mg of Fe0@POCN/CQDs was added, TC degradation efficiency gradually reached 70.3% after 60 min. After increasing the photocatalyst dosage to 25, 30, 35, 40 and 45 mg, the TC removal efficiency was increased to 78.8%, 86.7%, 89.4%, 92.5% and 95.6%, respectively, indicating that a larger Fe0@POCN/CQDs dosage resulted in a better TC removal efficiency. The results could be explained as that the more active sites on photocatalyst used to photocatalytic degradation organic pollutant. However, it can be observed that excessive dosage of photocatalyst could be detrimental to photocatalytic performance, the corresponding average photocatalytic degradation rate gradually decreased from 0.0586 to 0.0354 h−1. This is mainly related to the increase of Fe0@POCN/CQDs, the light transmittance of the solution decreases, and some catalysts cannot be fully utilized in the process (
                           Luo et al., 2019
                           ). Therefore, 30 mg was selected as the optimal Fe0@POCN/CQDs dosage to be used in the following experiments.
